	<h1>Case study: Maximising a couple&#39;s income from jobseeker&#39;s
  payments</h1>
	
<ul class="anchorlinks"></ul>
<div>
<p>Mary is working and earning â‚¬224 a week. Her days at work have been
reduced permanently to 3 days. She has an entitlement to Jobseekerâ€™s Benefit
(JB). As her days at work are permanently reduced she will be assessed for JB
as a part-time worker and not a systematic short-time worker. </p>

<p>John has been out of work for some time and his JB claim has come to an end.
He has applied for Jobseekerâ€™s Allowance (JA). He has been offered a
part-time job and will be working 2 days and earning â‚¬100 each week. </p>

<p>John and Mary have 2 children aged 7 and 12. They have no assessable means
other than that from employment. </p>

<p>What social welfare payments can John and Mary claim and which payments will
maximise their household income? </p>

<h3>Answer </h3>

<p>In the case of Mary and John, you must do 4 separate calculations to find
out which social welfare payment or combination of payments will maximise their
income. </p>

<p>You must calculate their social welfare entitlement based on the 4 following
situations: </p>
<ol><li>John claims JA for the whole family â€“ see â€˜Assessment 1â€™ below </li>
  <li>Mary claims JB for the whole family â€“ see â€˜Assessment 2â€™ below </li>
  <li>John claims JA and Mary claims Family Income Supplement (FIS) â€“ see
    â€˜Assessment 3â€™ below</li>
  <li>John and Mary claim separate social welfare payments: John claims JA and
    Mary claims JB â€“ see â€˜Assessment 4â€™ below.</li>
</ol><h3>Assessment 1: John claims JA for the family </h3>

<p>Personal rate â‚¬193 </p>

<p>IQA* rate â‚¬128.10 </p>

<p><u>IQC** rate â‚¬59.60</u> (for 2 children)</p>

<p>Total â‚¬380.70 </p>

<p>Less means â‚¬98.00 (from Maryâ€™s employment â€“ see Note 1 below) </p>

<p><u>Less means â‚¬36 </u>(from Johnâ€™s employment â€“ see Note 2 below) </p>

<p><strong>Total JA for John â‚¬246.70 </strong></p>

<p>*Increase for a Qualified Adult (IQA) </p>

<p>** Increase for a Qualified Child (IQC) </p>

<table border="1"><caption></caption>
  <col><tbody><tr><td>Total income for Assessment 1: 

        <p>Add their sources of income together to find their total income: </p>

        <p>Johnâ€™s JA + Maryâ€™s income from work + Johnâ€™s income from work
        = total income â‚¬246.70 + â‚¬224 + â‚¬100 = â‚¬570.70 </p>

        <p><strong>Total income = â‚¬570.70 </strong></p>
      </td>
    </tr></tbody></table><p></p>

<h3>Assessment 2: Mary claims JB for the family </h3>

<p>Personal rate â‚¬193 </p>

<p>IQA â‚¬128.10 (not reduced as Johnâ€™s earnings are only â‚¬100) </p>

<p><u>IQC â‚¬59.60</u> (for 2 children) </p>

<p>Total JB â‚¬380.70 </p>

<p>However, because Mary is working part-time 3 days each week, she is only
eligible to claim for JB for 2 days. She will get two-fifths (40%) of
â‚¬380.70.</p>

<p><strong>Maryâ€™s JB payment is â‚¬152.28 payment</strong> for 3 days of
unemployment. </p>

<table border="1"><caption></caption>
  <col><tbody><tr><td>Total income for Assessment 2: 

        <p>Add their sources of income together to find their total income: </p>

        <p>Maryâ€™s JB + Maryâ€™s income from work + Johnâ€™s income from work
        = total income </p>

        <p>â‚¬152.28 + â‚¬224 + â‚¬100 = â‚¬476.28 </p>

        <p><strong>Total income = â‚¬476.28</strong> </p>
      </td>
    </tr></tbody></table><p></p>

<h3>Assessment 3: John claims JA and Mary claims FIS</h3>

<p>1. Johnâ€™s JA claim: </p>

<p>Personal rate â‚¬193 </p>

<p>No IQA </p>

<p><u>Half-rate IQC â‚¬29.80</u> (for 2 children)</p>

<p>Total â‚¬222.80 </p>

<p>Less means â‚¬49 (half Maryâ€™s means â€“ see Note 1 and 3 below) </p>

<p><u>Less means â‚¬18 </u>(half Johnâ€™s means â€“ see Note 2 and 3 below)
<strong></strong></p>

<p><strong>Total JA for John â‚¬155.80</strong> </p>

<p></p>

<p>2. Maryâ€™s FIS claim: </p>

<p>Add their assessable income together: </p>

<p>Maryâ€™s income from work* â‚¬224 Johnâ€™s income from work* â‚¬100 </p>

<p><u>Johnâ€™s JA payment â‚¬155.80</u> </p>

<p>Total assessable income â‚¬479.80</p>

<p>*Income from work less disregards </p>

<table border="1"><caption></caption>
  <col><col><tbody><tr><td>FIS limit for couple with 2 children</td>
      <td>â‚¬612</td>
    </tr><tr><td>Less familyâ€™s assessable income </td>
      <td><u>â‚¬479.80</u></td>
    </tr><tr><td></td>
      <td>â‚¬132.20</td>
    </tr></tbody></table><p>60% of 132.20 = â‚¬79.32</p>

<p><strong>FIS payment for Mary = â‚¬80 (rounded up) </strong></p>

<table border="1"><caption></caption>
  <col><tbody><tr><td>Total income for Assessment 3: 

        <p>Add their sources of income together to find their total income: </p>

        <p>Maryâ€™s FIS payment + Maryâ€™s income from work + Johnâ€™s income
        from work + Johnâ€™s JA payment = total income</p>

        <p>â‚¬80 + â‚¬224 + â‚¬100 + â‚¬155.80 = â‚¬559.80</p>

        <p><strong>Total income = â‚¬559.80 </strong></p>
      </td>
    </tr></tbody></table><p></p>

<h3>Assessment 4: John and Mary claim separate jobseekerâ€™s payments </h3>

<p>1. Johnâ€™s JA claim for himself only: </p>

<p>Personal rate â‚¬193</p>

<p>No IQA </p>

<p>Half IQC â‚¬29.80 (for 2 children) </p>

<p>Total â‚¬222.80 </p>

<p>Less means â‚¬49 (half Maryâ€™s means â€“ see Note 1 and 3 below) </p>

<p>Less means â‚¬18 (half Johnâ€™s means â€“ see Note 2 and 3 below) </p>

<p><strong>Total JA for John â‚¬155.80 </strong></p>

<p>2. Maryâ€™s JB claim for herself only: </p>

<p>Personal rate â‚¬193 </p>

<p>No IQA </p>

<p>Half IQC â‚¬29.80 (for 2 children) </p>

<p>Total JB â‚¬222.80 </p>

<p>However, because she is working part-time 3 days each week, she will get two
fifths of â‚¬222.80. </p>

<p><strong>Maryâ€™s JB payment is â‚¬89.12</strong> - payment for 3 days of
unemployment. </p>

<p><strong>Maximum payment rule: </strong></p>

<p>Where separate payments are being claimed you must allow for maximum payment
in your calculation â€“ see Note 4 below. </p>

<p>â‚¬155.80 + â‚¬222.80 = â‚¬378.60, this amount is not greater than the
maximum payment of â‚¬380.70, so Johnâ€™s JA payment will not be reduced. </p>

<table border="1"><caption></caption>
  <col><tbody><tr><td>Total income for Assessment 4: 

        <p>Add their sources of income together to find their total income: </p>

        <p>Johnâ€™s JA payment + Johnâ€™s income from work + Maryâ€™s JB
        payment + Maryâ€™s income from work = total income </p>

        <p>â‚¬155.80 + â‚¬100 + â‚¬89.12 + â‚¬224 = â‚¬568.92</p>

        <p><strong>Total income = â‚¬568.92 </strong></p>
      </td>
    </tr></tbody></table><p></p>

<h3>Conclusion </h3>

<p>In this case study, the family are very slightly better off with Assessment
1 (John claims JA for the whole family). However Assessment 4 (John and Mary
claim separate jobseeker payments) might be better since both partners are
eligible for training and education schemes in their own right. </p>

<p><strong>Note 1 </strong></p>

<p>Maryâ€™s means from work for Johnâ€™s JA assessment are calculated as
follows: </p>

<p>Income from work of â‚¬224 less â‚¬20 for each day worked up to a maximum of
â‚¬60 (3 days). 60% of the balance is assessed as means. </p>

<p>â‚¬224 - â‚¬60 = â‚¬164 </p>

<p>60% of â‚¬164 = â‚¬98 (rounded off) </p>

<p><strong></strong>Maryâ€™s means are calculated as <strong>â‚¬98 </strong></p>

<p><strong>Note 2 </strong></p>

<p>Johnâ€™s means from work for JA are calculated as follows: </p>

<p><strong>1. Calculate Johnâ€™s average daily earnings: </strong></p>

<p>Get his total weekly assessable earnings from employment and divide by the
number of days he worked that week. </p>

<p>Total weekly earnings Ã· number of days worked = average daily earnings. </p>

<p>â‚¬100 Ã· 2 = â‚¬50</p>

<p><strong>2. Next calculate Johnâ€™s daily means from work </strong></p>

<p>First disregard any income not taken into account. Income not taken into
account is â‚¬20 for each day worked up to a maximum of â‚¬60 (3 days). Then
60% of the balance is assessed as means. </p>

<p>Average daily earnings - â‚¬20 = total </p>

<p>Total x 60% = daily means from work. </p>

<p>â‚¬50 â€“ â‚¬20 = 30 </p>

<p>30 x 60% = â‚¬18 </p>

<p><strong>3. Finally, find Johnâ€™s weekly means from work </strong></p>

<p>Multiply his daily means by the number of days worked. </p>

<p>Daily means from work x number of days worked = weekly means from work. </p>

<p>â‚¬18 x 2 = â‚¬36 </p>

<p><strong></strong>Johnâ€™s means are assessed as <strong>â‚¬36</strong></p>

<p><strong>Note 3 </strong></p>

<p><strong>Joint means are halved if</strong> spouse, civil partner or
cohabitant is:</p>
<ul><li>Getting a social welfare payment (except Child Benefit, Early Childcare
    Supplement, Disablement Pension, a guardian's payment, Supplementary
    Welfare Allowance, Domiciliary Care Allowance or half-rate Carer's
    Allowance)</li>
  <li>On a Further Education and Training (FET) course or on a VTOS course and
    getting an allowance in their own right</li>
</ul><p>Maryâ€™s means from work is â‚¬98 â€“ see â€˜Note 1â€™ above. Johnâ€™s means
from work is â‚¬36 â€“ see â€˜Note 2â€™ above. </p>

<p>In Assessments 3 and 4 the couples combined means is halved because both are
getting social welfare payments. In Assessment 3 Mary is getting FIS and John
is getting JA. In Assessment 4 Mary is getting JB and John is getting JA. </p>

<p>As a result, Maryâ€™s means is â‚¬49 and Johnâ€™s means is â‚¬18 for
Assessments 3 and 4. </p>

<p><strong>Note 4 </strong></p>

<p>Maximum payment rule: </p>

<p>If one of a couple is claiming Jobseeker's Allowance and the other is
getting of one of the social welfare payments listed below, <strong>the total
amount paid to the couple cannot exceed the maximum amount paid to one person
(including dependants) on one social welfare payment</strong>. However, you can
choose the higher-rate payment as the primary payment. </p>
<ul><li>Illness Benefit</li>
  <li>Disablement Pension (when paid with Illness Benefit or Incapacity
    Supplement)</li>
  <li>Injury Benefit</li>
  <li>Invalidity Pension</li>
  <li>State Pension (Non-Contributory)</li>
  <li>State Pension (Contributory)</li>
  <li>Jobseeker's Benefit</li>
  <li>Jobseeker's Allowance</li>
  <li>Pre-Retirement Allowance (PRETA)</li>
  <li>Farm Assist </li>
</ul><p>Where the spouse, civil partner or cohabitant of a JA claimant is getting
JB, the Department of Social Protection assesses the maximum payment based on
the premise that the person is fully unemployed. This means, if the claimant is
getting a reduced JB (for example 2 days JB) because they are working, they
will be assessed as though they are getting full-rate JB. </p>

<p>In the case study above the maximum payment for the family is: Personal rate
+ IQA + IQC (full rate for 2 children) = maximum payment for the family </p>

<p>â‚¬193 + â‚¬128.10 + â‚¬59.60 = â‚¬380.70</p>

<p>In Assessment 4 of the case study, Johnâ€™s JA payment and Maryâ€™s JB
payment combined are less than the maximum payment for the family, as a result,
there is no change to Johnâ€™s JA payment. </p>

<p>If Mary and Johnâ€™s combined JA and JB payment was greater than the maximum
payment for the family, Johnâ€™s JA payment would be reduced by the difference.
</p>
